'''Nicolas Jackson''' (born 20 June 2001) is a Senegalese professional [[association footballer|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] and [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for  {{English football updater|Chelsea}} club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], and the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].

Jackson played for [[Casa Sports]] in Senegal before joining [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in 2019. After a loan to [[CD Mirandés|Mirandés]] in the [[Segunda División]], he broke through in the [[Villarreal CF B|reserve team]] and made his first-team debut in [[La Liga]] in 2021. In 2023, he signed an eight-year deal at Chelsea for a reported fee of £32&nbsp;million.

Jackson made his senior international debut for Senegal in 2022. He was selected in the Senegalese squads for the [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] and the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]] and [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]].

==Early life==
Jackson's birthplace is uncertain: several sources claim he was born in [[Banjul]], The Gambia,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Street football to Premier League: Nicolas Jackson's road to Chelsea |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jul/04/street-football-to-premier-league-nicolas-jacksons-road-to-chelsea |access-date=26 October 2024 |work=The Guardian |date=4 July 2023|quote=Born in Banjul, the Gambia, he was raised in Ziguinchor, in the rural Casamance region of southern Senegal, [...]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gambie : Nicolas Jackson n'a pas oublié sa terre natale, découvrez le beau geste de l'international sénégalais (photos) |trans-title=The Gambia: Nicolas Jackson has not forgotten the land of his birth, discover the beautiful gesture of the Senegalese international (photos) |url=https://www.senenews.com/actualites/societe/gambie-nicolas-jackson-na-pas-oublie-sa-terre-natale-decouvrez-le-beau-geste-de-linternational-senegalais-photos_498009.html |access-date=26 October 2024 |publisher=Senenews |date=26 June 2024 |language=French |archive-date=10 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240910205135/https://www.senenews.com/actualites/societe/gambie-nicolas-jackson-na-pas-oublie-sa-terre-natale-decouvrez-le-beau-geste-de-linternational-senegalais-photos_498009.html |url-status=live }}</ref> while Chelsea and Bayern official profiles claim he was born in {{ill|Djibonker|fr}}, Senegal,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/kidsclub/de/news/2025/09/das-ist-neuzugang-nicolas-jackson |title=FC Bayern verpflichtet Nicolas Jackson |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=1 September 2025 }}</ref> to a Gambian father and Senegalese mother. In 2017, in the aftermath of the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]], the family moved to [[Ziguinchor]], Senegal.<ref name=FIFA>{{cite web|title=Nicolas Jackson arrives at Chelsea, hoping to emulate African heroes|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/nicolas-jackson-arrives-at-chelsea-hoping-to-emulate-african-heroes|publisher=FIFA|access-date=30 January 2024|date=6 July 2023|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240130002152/https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/nicolas-jackson-arrives-at-chelsea-hoping-to-emulate-african-heroes}}<!-- internet archive shows blue page without text for this url --></ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ceesay|first1=Ebrima|title=NICHOLAS JACKSON: GAMBIA'S LOSS IS SENEGAL'S GAIN|url=https://alkambatimes.com/nicholas-jackson-gambias-loss-is-senegals-gain|access-date=20 February 2024|work=Alkamba Times|date=3 September 2023|archive-date=30 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240130002152/https://alkambatimes.com/nicholas-jackson-gambias-loss-is-senegals-gain/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Jackson began playing for local side ASC Tilene before joining [[Casa Sports]],<ref name=SNA>{{cite web|url=https://sportnewsafrica.com/en/at-a-glance/nicholas-jackson-the-rise-from-casasport-to-chelsea|title=Nicholas Jackson: The rise from Casa Sport to Chelsea|publisher=Sport News Africa|date=30 June 2023|accessdate=30 June 2023|archive-date=30 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230630190724/https://sportnewsafrica.com/en/at-a-glance/nicholas-jackson-the-rise-from-casasport-to-chelsea/|url-status=live}}</ref> where he was a part of the first team squad during the [[2018–19 Senegal Premier League|2018–19 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsfp.sn/player/nicolas-jackson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240421080248/https://lsfp.sn/player/nicolas-jackson|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 April 2024|title=Nicolas Jackson|publisher=Ligue Sénégalaise de Football Professionnel|language=fr|accessdate=7 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/jackson-on-his-journey-from-street-footballer-to-chelsea-star|title=Jackson on his journey from street footballer to Chelsea star|publisher=Chelsea FC|date=16 September 2023|accessdate=19 September 2023|archive-date=29 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929074307/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/jackson-on-his-journey-from-street-footballer-to-chelsea-star|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also named [[man of the match]] in a 1–1 [[Ligue 1 (Senegal)|Ligue 1]] draw against [[AS Pikine]] on 16 November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsfp.sn/as-pikine-vs-casa-sports-1-1-les-pikinois-tenus-en-echec-a-domicile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240421080254/https://lsfp.sn/as-pikine-vs-casa-sports-1-1-les-pikinois-tenus-en-echec-a-domicile|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 April 2024|title=AS Pikine vs Casa Sports (1–1): les Pikinois tenus en échec à domicile|trans-title=AS Pikine vs Casa Sports (1–1): the ''Pikinois'' held in check at home|publisher=Ligue Sénégalaise de Football Professionnel|language=fr|date=23 November 2018|accessdate=7 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://africafoot.com/des-verts-de-la-casamance-aux-blues-londoniens-la-fulgurante-ascension-de-nicolas-jackson|title=Des verts de la Casamance aux Blues londoniens, la fulgurante ascension de Nicolas Jackson|trans-title=From the greens of Casamance to the London Blues, the meteoric rise of Nicolas Jackson|publisher=Africa Foot|language=fr|date=25 June 2023|accessdate=30 June 2023|archive-date=30 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230630191039/https://africafoot.com/des-verts-de-la-casamance-aux-blues-londoniens-la-fulgurante-ascension-de-nicolas-jackson/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Villarreal===
In September 2019, Jackson agreed to a contract with [[La Liga]] side [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.galsenfoot.com/mercato-diomansy-camara-fait-signer-un-joueur-du-casa-sport-a-villarreal|title=Mercato: Diomansy Camara fait signer un joueur du Casa Sport à Villarreal|trans-title=Transfer market: Diomansy Camara signs a Casa Sport player at Villarreal|publisher=Galsenfoot|language=fr|date=4 September 2019|accessdate=7 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castelloninformacion.com/nicolas-jackson-reforzara-filiales-villarreal-delantero-senegales|title=El Villarreal firma al joven delantero Nicolás Jackson el 'Neymar' senegalés para uno de sus dos filiales|trans-title=Villarreal sign young forward Nicolás Jackson the Senegalese 'Neymar' to one of their reserve teams|publisher=Castellón Información|language=es|date=3 September 2019|accessdate=7 October 2020|archive-date=9 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009081547/https://www.castelloninformacion.com/nicolas-jackson-reforzara-filiales-villarreal-delantero-senegales/|url-status=live}}</ref> being assigned to the Juvenil A squad.

====Loan to Mirandés====
On 5 October 2020, Jackson was loaned to [[Segunda División]] side [[CD Mirandés|Mirandés]] for the [[2020–21 Segunda División|2020–21 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/28694-jackson-will-play-on-loan-at-mirandes|title=Jackson will play on loan at Mirandés|publisher=Villarreal CF|date=5 October 2020|accessdate=7 October 2020|archive-date=30 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221030162308/https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/28694-jackson-will-play-on-loan-at-mirandes|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his professional debut thirteen days later, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Antonio Caballero (footballer)|Antonio Caballero]] in a 0–0 home draw against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/mirandes-vs-mallorca/cronica/2020/10/18/5f8c7994268e3e07368b45ed.html|title=Un cerocerismo injusto por lo visto en Anduva|trans-title=An unfair 0–0 for what it was seen in Anduva|work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=18 October 2020|accessdate=18 October 2020|archive-date=18 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418045210/https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/mirandes-vs-mallorca/cronica/2020/10/18/5f8c7994268e3e07368b45ed.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Jackson scored his first professional goal on 28 November 2020, netting the opener in a 1–1 home draw against [[CD Castellón|Castellón]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/mirandes-vs-castellon/cronica/2020/11/28/5fc2ad0d46163f31b98b459a.html|title=El Castellón se crece y araña un buen punto de Anduva|trans-title=Castellón grow big and scratch a good point out of Anduva|work=Marca|location=Spain|language=es|date=28 November 2020|accessdate=30 November 2020|archive-date=18 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230318133423/https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/mirandes-vs-castellon/cronica/2020/11/28/5fc2ad0d46163f31b98b459a.html|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his only goal of [[2020–21 Segunda División|the season]] as the Jabatos finished in 10th place.

==== Breakthrough ====
Upon returning, Jackson played for Villarreal's [[Villarreal CF B|B-team]] in [[Primera División RFEF]], scoring seven goals as the side [[2021–22 Primera División RFEF|achieved promotion to the second division]]. He made his first team – and [[La Liga]] – debut on 3 October 2021, replacing [[Arnaut Danjuma]] late into a 2–0 home win over [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2021/10/11/primera/1633964587_987485.html|title=Nicolas Jackson, la nueva perla amarilla que ya perfila Emery|trans-title=Nicolas Jackson, the new yellow pearl who Emery already shapes up|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=es|date=11 October 2021|accessdate=24 May 2023|archive-date=24 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524212635/https://as.com/futbol/2021/10/11/primera/1633964587_987485.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Jackson scored his first goal in the top tier on 13 August 2022, netting the opener in a 3–0 away win over [[Real Valladolid]]. Thirteen days later, he and teammate [[Álex Baena]] were promoted to the main squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/35264-baena-and-jackson-officially-become-first-team-players|title=Baena and Jackson officially become first-team players|publisher=Villarreal CF|date=26 August 2022|accessdate=26 August 2022|archive-date=26 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220826220932/https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/35264-baena-and-jackson-officially-become-first-team-players|url-status=live}}</ref>

In January 2023, Villarreal agreed a [[Pound sterling|£]]22.5&nbsp;million deal from [[AFC Bournemouth]] for the signing of Jackson, but he failed his medical due to [[hamstring]] issues, and the transfer did not materialise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/23282482.bournemouths-swoop-southampton-target-jackson-fails-medical|title=Bournemouth's swoop for Southampton target Jackson fails after medical|work=[[Southern Daily Echo]]|date=27 January 2023|accessdate=24 May 2023|archive-date=24 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524205116/https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/23282482.bournemouths-swoop-southampton-target-jackson-fails-medical/|url-status=live}}</ref> After returning to action in March, he scored nine goals within the months of April and May, which included braces against [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]], [[Athletic Bilbao]] and [[Cádiz CF|Cádiz]].

===Chelsea===
[[File:Nicolas Jackson 20042025 (1).jpg|thumb|left|250px|Jackson with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in April 2025]]

On 30 June 2023, Jackson signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on an eight-year deal through 2031 for a fee reported to be [[Pound sterling|£]]32&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicolas Jackson joins the Blues|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/nicolas-jackson-joins-the-blues|date=30 June 2023|access-date=1 August 2023|publisher=Chelsea F.C.|archive-date=30 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230630180455/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/nicolas-jackson-joins-the-blues|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 August, he made his debut for the club in a 1–1 draw against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12937533/chelsea-1-1-liverpool-mauricio-pochettinos-side-fight-back-to-draw-his-first-premier-league-game-in-charge |title=Chelsea 1–1 Liverpool: Mauricio Pochettino's side fight back to draw his first Premier League game in charge|publisher=Sky Sports|date=13 August 2023 |access-date=14 August 2023|archive-date=15 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815002214/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12937533/chelsea-1-1-liverpool-mauricio-pochettinos-side-fight-back-to-draw-his-first-premier-league-game-in-charge|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first Chelsea goal on 25 August 2023 against newly promoted side [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], helping Chelsea to a 3–0 win at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66540847 |title=Chelsea 3–0 Luton Town: Raheem Sterling double helps Blues see off Hatters|publisher=BBC|date=25 August 2023 |access-date=26 August 2023|archive-date=27 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240127231141/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66540847|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 November, Jackson scored twice in second-half stoppage time to complete a [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] in a 4–1 away win over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea beat nine-man Tottenham in chaotic epic|work=BBC Sport| url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67258895|access-date=2023-11-06|archive-date=7 November 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231107020410/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67258895|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored again in the next match against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], which ended in a 4–4 home draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea 4–4 Manchester City: Cole Palmer hits late penalty to deny former club victory|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67325041|website=BBC Sport|date=12 November 2023|access-date=4 January 2024|archive-date=22 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231222231829/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67325041|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 15 April 2024, Jackson scored his tenth Premier League goal of the season, and provided an assist for [[Cole Palmer]]'s goal in a 6–0 win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. As Palmer had already reached double digits in league goals, this became the first Chelsea season since [[2017–18 Chelsea F.C. season|2017–18]] in which two players had scored ten or more Premier League goals in a season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea 6–0 Everton: Cole Palmer scores four including 16-minute hat-trick|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68758438|website=BBC Sport|date=15 April 2024|access-date=16 April 2024|archive-date=16 April 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240416060617/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68758438|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 May 2024, Jackson scored twice and provided an assist for Palmer in a 5–0 home win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea 5–0 West Ham: Nicolas Jackson nets brace as Blues cruise to big derby win|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/chelsea-fc-vs-west-ham-premier-league-result-jackson-b1155810.html|website=The Standard|date=5 May 2024|access-date=29 June 2024|archive-date=29 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240629101249/https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/chelsea-fc-vs-west-ham-premier-league-result-jackson-b1155810.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored 14 league goals across 35 appearances, making him the second highest African goal scorer in the 2023–24 season only behind Liverpool's [[Mohamed Salah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Top African Goal Scorers In Premier League 2023/2024|url=https://africanfolder.com/african-goal-scorers-in-premier-league-2023-2024/|website=[[African Folder]]|date=25 May 2024}}</ref>

On 13 September 2024, Jackson signed a two-year contract extension with Chelsea, extending his contract until 2033.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chelsea FC |title=Nicolas Jackson signs contract extension! |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/nicolas-jackson-signs-chelsea-contract-extension |access-date=2024-09-15 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |archive-date=13 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240913161851/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/nicolas-jackson-signs-chelsea-contract-extension |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] award for October 2024 for the opening goal of a 2–1 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 27 October.<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 October 2024 |title=Chelsea 2–1 Newcastle: Cole Palmer scored his seventh goal of the season as Chelsea beat Newcastle to continue their impressive start. |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cvgl519dd0mt |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=8 November 2024 |title=Jackson wins Guinness Goal of the Month award for October 2024 |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4164754 |access-date=27 January 2025 |publisher=[[Premier League]] |archive-date=12 November 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241112180348/https://www.premierleague.com/news/4164754 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 1 May 2025, Jackson scored a brace in the first leg of the [[2024–25 UEFA Conference League knockout phase|Conference League semi-final]] which ended in a 4–1 away win over [[Djurgårdens IF Fotboll|Djurgården]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rajan |first=Adwaidh |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c5y6r0n93qkt |title=Djurgården 1–4 Chelsea |publisher=UEFA |date=1 May 2025 }}</ref> He was later sent off on 11 May for a deliberate elbow in a Premier League match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 May 2025 |title=How expensive will Chelsea's Premier League loss at Newcastle prove to be? |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cj6rk21k3j2o |access-date=2025-05-12 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 28 May, he netted the second goal for Chelsea in a 4–1 win over [[Real Betis]] in the [[2025 UEFA Conference League final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaconferenceleague/news/0299-1dde1ba33803-6370dd142717-1000--real-betis-1-4-chelsea-the-blues-complete-set-with-confe/ |title=Real Betis 1–4 Chelsea: The Blues complete set with Conference League success |publisher=UEFA |date=28 May 2025 }}</ref> A month later, on 20 June, he was shown a straight red card for a reckless challenge just four minutes after coming on as a substitute in a 3–1 loss to [[CR Flamengo|Flamengo]] during the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kinsella |first=Nizaar |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c3en8pl22kyo |title='Stupid, stupid, stupid' – Jackson opens door for Delap |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 June 2025 }}</ref>

====Loan to Bayern Munich====
On 1 September 2025, Jackson joined [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on a season-long loan for a reported fee of €16.5m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea striker Jackson joins Bayern Munich in £70.5m deal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/czr6rm8j4dyo |access-date=1 September 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 September 2025}}</ref> Later that month, on 30 September, he scored his first goal for the club in a 5–1 away win over [[Cypriot First Division]] club [[Pafos FC|Pafos]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/matches/profis/champions-league/2025-2026/paphos-fc-fc-bayern-muenchen-30-09-2025/report |title=Bayern march on with 5-1 win over Pafos |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=30 September 2025 }}</ref>

On 19 April 2026, he won the [[2025–26 Bundesliga]] with Bayern Munich and their 35th league title, starting and scoring the second goal during a 4–2 home win over [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c89558d5d5nt |title=Bayern Munich 4–2 Stuttgart |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 April 2026 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kicker.de/bayern-gegen-stuttgart-2026-bundesliga-5051012/spielbericht |title=Bayern dreht nach Rückstand auf und kürt sich vorzeitig zum Deutschen Meister |publisher=Kicker|language=German|date=19 April 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sofascore.com/sv/football/match/vfb-stuttgart-fc-bayern-munchen/xdbsCdb#id:14065222 | title = Bayern-Stuttgart |publisher=Sofascore | language = en | date = 19 April 2026 | access-date = 19 April 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Jackson represented [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] at [[Senegal national under-20 football team|under-20 level]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsfp.sn/matches-amicaux-les-u-20-invites-en-arabie-saoudite|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303120358/https://lsfp.sn/matches-amicaux-les-u-20-invites-en-arabie-saoudite/|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 March 2024|title=Matches amicaux – Les U 20 invités en Arabie saoudite|trans-title=Friendlies – U-20 invited to Saudi Arabia|publisher=Ligue Sénégalaise de Football Professionnel|language=fr|date=28 December 2018|accessdate=7 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsfp.sn/preparation-de-matches-amicaux-lequipe-nationale-juniors-en-stage-a-partir-de-lundi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240301000607/https://lsfp.sn/preparation-de-matches-amicaux-lequipe-nationale-juniors-en-stage-a-partir-de-lundi/|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 March 2024|title=Préparation de matches amicaux : L'équipe nationale juniors en stage à partir de lundi|trans-title=Preparation for friendly matches: The national junior team in training camp from Monday|publisher=Ligue Sénégalaise de Football Professionnel|language=fr|date=4 January 2019|accessdate=7 October 2020}}</ref> receiving his first call-up in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seneplus.com/sports/premiere-selection-pour-nicolas-jackson-du-casa-sports|title=Première sélection pour Nicolas Jackson du Casa-Sports|trans-title=First call-up of Nicolas Jackson from Casa Sports|publisher=SenePlus|language=fr|date=15 November 2018|accessdate=7 October 2020|archive-date=26 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230526152103/https://www.seneplus.com/sports/premiere-selection-pour-nicolas-jackson-du-casa-sports|url-status=live}}</ref>

After being called up to the full side by manager [[Aliou Cissé]] for two friendlies in September 2022, Jackson was included in the 26-man list for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] on 11 November 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fsfoot.sn/aliou-cisse-devoile-les-26-lions-pour-qatar|title=Aliou Cisse dévoile les 26 Lions pour Qatar|trans-title=Aliou Cissé unveils 26 Lions for Qatar|publisher=[[Senegalese Football Federation]]|date=11 November 2022|access-date=11 November 2022|language=fr|archive-date=12 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112093530/https://www.fsfoot.sn/aliou-cisse-devoile-les-26-lions-pour-qatar|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his full international debut in Senegal's opening match of the competition, replacing [[Krépin Diatta]] in a 2–0 loss against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://castellonplaza.com/jackson-debuta-con-senegal-en-el-mundial-y-cae-ante-paises-bajos|title=Jackson debuta con Senegal en el Mundial y cae ante Países Bajos|trans-title=Jackson debuts with Senegal in the World Cup and suffer defeat against the Netherlands|publisher=Castellón Plaza|language=es|date=21 November 2022|accessdate=24 May 2023|archive-date=2 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230202153443/https://castellonplaza.com/jackson-debuta-con-senegal-en-el-mundial-y-cae-ante-paises-bajos|url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2023, he was named in Senegal's squad for the postponed [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal and Sadio Mane set for defence of title|date=29 December 2023|access-date=1 January 2024|work=BBC Sport Africa|archive-date=14 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240114231958/https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|url-status=live}}</ref> He came on as a substitute in all four games as the defending champions made it to the last 16.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mtuta |first1=Lukhanyo |title=5 top stars who've flopped at AFCON 2023 |url=https://www.snl24.com/kickoff/worldnews/afcon/5-top-stars-peter-shalulile-andre-onana-mohamed-salah-riyad-mahrez-nicolas-jackson-who-flopped-at-afcon-2023-20240130 |access-date=26 October 2024 |work=[[Kick Off (magazine)|Kick Off]] |date=30 January 2024}}</ref>

On 11 October 2024, he scored his first international goal, concluding a 4–0 home win over [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]] in [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jackson breaks duck as Senegal runs riot |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-au/football/africa-cup-of-nations/articles-video/jackson-breaks-duck-as-senegal-runs-riot-2024-10-11 |access-date=26 October 2024 |publisher=beIN Sports |date=11 October 2024}}</ref>

He was part of the [[2025 African Cup of Nations]] with Senegal. He scored a brace in the opening game against [[Botswana national football team|Botswana]]. Later, in the round of 16, he assisted [[Papa Gueye]] in a 3-1 victory for them against [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]]. Later, he became AFCON champion with Senegal after defeating Morocco in the final.

